To style your Material-UI React component to be in the middle of the screen, you can use CSS styles. Here's an example of how you can achieve that:

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import { makeStyles } from '@material-ui/core/styles';
import Paper from '@material-ui/core/Paper';

const useStyles = makeStyles((theme) => ({
  root: {
    display: 'flex',
    justifyContent: 'center',
    alignItems: 'center',
    height: '100vh',
  },
  paper: {
    padding: theme.spacing(2),
    textAlign: 'center',
    maxWidth: 400,
    width: '100%',
  },
}));

const MiddleComponent = () => {
  const classes = useStyles();

  return (
    <div className={classes.root}>
      <Paper className={classes.paper}>
        {/* Your component content goes here */}
      </Paper>
    </div>
  );
};

export default MiddleComponent;
```

In this example, we are using the `makeStyles` hook from Material-UI to define custom styles. The `root` class is applied to the outer `div` element and is responsible for centering the content. It uses `display: flex`, `justifyContent: center`, and `alignItems: center` properties to center the inner content vertically and horizontally. The `height: '100vh'` ensures that the component takes up the entire viewport height.

The `paper` class is applied to the `Paper` component, which is just an example of a Material-UI component. You can replace it with any other Material-UI component or your custom component. The `padding`, `textAlign`, `maxWidth`, and `width` properties are used to style the `Paper` component, ensuring it stays in the center and has a maximum width of 400 pixels.

By wrapping your component content inside the `Paper` component and the `root` div with custom styles, your Material-UI React component will be styled to appear in the middle of the screen.

