To create a gallery section that displays an image slider in a pop-up when clicked on, you can use the following steps:

Step 1: Include a lightweight image gallery library. For example, you can use Fancybox or BaguetteBox.

Step 2: Add a container element for your gallery section in your HTML markup. For instance:

```html
<div id="gallery">
  <img class="gallery-image" src="image1.jpg" alt="Image 1">
  <img class="gallery-image" src="image2.jpg" alt="Image 2">
  <!-- Add more images here -->
</div>
```

Step 3: Include the necessary CSS and JS files for the chosen gallery library. Make sure to follow the installation instructions provided by the library.

Step 4: Initialize the gallery script with proper configuration. For instance, using Fancybox:

```javascript
$(document).ready(function() {
  $('#gallery').on('click', '.gallery-image', function() {
    $.fancybox.open({
      // Configure options as needed
      // For example:
      // type: 'image',
      // image: { preload: true },
      // gallery: { enabled: true }
      // ...
      src: $(this).attr('src'),
      caption: $(this).attr('alt')
    });
  });
});
```

In this example, we attach a click event listener to the images inside the gallery container. When an image is clicked, we use Fancybox's `open` method to display the image in a pop-up slider. Customize the options inside `$.fancybox.open` to fit your requirements (e.g., image preload, gallery navigation, etc.). The `src` and `caption` attributes of the clicked image are passed to the pop-up as the source and caption.

Step 5: Style your gallery section and pop-up as needed using CSS.

Make sure to replace `image1.jpg`, `image2.jpg`, and the `alt` attributes with the appropriate image sources and captions in your gallery section. Adjust the initialization code based on the chosen gallery library.

Remember to consult the documentation and examples provided by the specific image gallery library you are using for additional customization options and usage details.
